Step 1. Determine Total Liabilities and Owner’s Equity from the balance sheet.  
• Total Assets = 15,200,446.16  
• Total Owner’s Equity = 13,707,199.17  
• Therefore, Total Liabilities = Total Assets – Total Equity = 15,200,446.16 – 13,707,199.17 = 1,493,246.99  

Step 2. Calculate Debt to Equity Ratio.  
Debt to Equity Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Owner’s Equity = 1,493,246.99 / 13,707,199.17 ≈ 0.109, which rounds to 0.11.

Step 3. Determine Net Profit Margin.  
Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100  
From the income statement:  
• Net Profit = 707,199.17  
• Total Revenue = 5,064,939.23  
Net Profit Margin ≈ (707,199.17 / 5,064,939.23) × 100 ≈ 13.97%

Step 4. Calculate Return on Assets (ROA).  
ROA = (Net Profit / Total Assets) × 100  
Total Assets = 15,200,446.16  
Thus, ROA ≈ (707,199.17 / 15,200,446.16) × 100 ≈ 4.65% (approximately 4.66% when rounded)

Step 5. Calculate Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio.  
The ratio is calculated as:  
Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio = Total Revenue / Average Accounts Receivable  
From the balance sheet:  
• Beginning Accounts Receivable = 0.00  
• Ending Accounts Receivable = 1,851,327.29  
Average Accounts Receivable = (0 + 1,851,327.29) / 2 = 925,663.645  
Thus, Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio ≈ 5,064,939.23 / 925,663.645 ≈ 5.47

Now, we present the final answers in the required JSON format.

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.11",
    "Net Profit Margin": "13.97%",
    "Return on Assets (ROA)": "4.66%",
    "Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio": "5.47"
  }
}
